          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "80 grams of protein in a day looks like: 2 eggs at breakfast (12g), a turkey sandwich at lunch (22g), a small chicken breast at dinner (28g), and a handful of nuts as a snack (6g). It's a day that looks and feels healthy — but for most men over 40, it's 40 to 60 grams short of what's needed to preserve muscle mass."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Is 80 grams of protein enough for a man over 40?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "No. For men over 40, research consistently supports a minimum of 1.2 grams of protein per kilogram of bodyweight — roughly 0.55 grams per pound — to preserve muscle mass. For a 180-pound man, that's around 100 grams minimum. At 80 grams, most men over 40 are in a chronic protein deficit that accelerates the muscle loss process known as sarcopenia."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What happens if men over 40 only eat 80g of protein a day?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Men over 40 eating only 80 grams of protein daily are likely accelerating sarcopenia — the age-related loss of muscle mass and strength. After 40, the body becomes less efficient at using dietary protein to build and repair muscle, a condition called anabolic resistance. This means you need more protein than a younger man just to achieve the same muscle maintenance response. 80 grams is not enough to overcome this threshold for most men."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How much protein does a man over 40 actually need per day?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Research supports 1.2 to 1.6 grams of protein per kilogram of bodyweight for men over 40 — that is 0.55 to 0.73 grams per pound. For a 180-pound man, that means 100 to 130 grams daily. The government RDA of 0.8 grams per kilogram (0.36 grams per pound) was set to prevent deficiency in young adults, not to preserve muscle mass as men age."
        }
      },
