    <p>That day has vegetables. Lean protein. Whole grains. A piece of fruit. By most people's definition of "eating well," that's a solid day. But for a man over 40, it's 40 to 50 grams short of what the research says is needed to preserve muscle mass.</p>

    <h2>How 80g Compares to What You Actually Need</h2>

    <p>Here's where American men get confused — and it's not their fault. The official government recommendation (the RDA) for protein is <strong>0.8 grams per kilogram of bodyweight</strong> — that's roughly <strong>0.36 grams per pound</strong>. For a 180-pound man, that comes out to about 65 grams per day.</p>

    <p>So at 80 grams, you're actually <em>above</em> the government recommendation. That feels fine. That feels adequate. The problem is the RDA was set in 1985 to prevent protein deficiency in healthy young adults. It was never designed to preserve muscle mass in aging men.</p>

