    <h2>What the Research Actually Says About Protein After 40</h2>

    <p>The science on this is consistent across dozens of studies. Men over 40 need significantly more protein than the RDA suggests — not because the RDA is wrong for young adults, but because aging changes how efficiently your body uses dietary protein.</p>

    <p>Here's what research-backed guidelines actually look like, in both kilograms and pounds so there's no confusion:</p>

    <table class="food-table">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Goal</th>
          <th>Per kg of bodyweight</th>
          <th>Per lb of bodyweight</th>
          <th>For a 180 lb man</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Government RDA (deficiency prevention)</td>
          <td>0.8g/kg</td>
          <td>0.36g/lb</td>
          <td class="red-col">~65g</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Minimum for muscle preservation after 40</td>
          <td>1.2g/kg</td>
          <td>0.55g/lb</td>
          <td class="protein-col">~100g</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Optimal for muscle maintenance after 40</td>
          <td>1.4g/kg</td>
          <td>0.64g/lb</td>
          <td class="protein-col">~115g</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Active recomposition target</td>
          <td>1.6g/kg</td>
          <td>0.73g/lb</td>
          <td class="protein-col">~130g</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <p>At 80 grams per day, a 180-pound man is eating at <strong>0.98g/kg (0.44g/lb)</strong> — well above the RDA, but well below the minimum threshold for muscle preservation that research actually supports for men over 40.</p>

    <h2>What Happens to Your Muscle at 80g Per Day</h2>

    <p>After 40, a condition called <strong>anabolic resistance</strong> sets in. Your muscles become less efficient at using dietary protein to build and repair tissue. A younger man might need 20g of protein at a meal to trigger a meaningful muscle protein synthesis response. After 40, that threshold rises — you need more protein per meal, and more total protein per day, just to achieve the same maintenance effect.</p>

    <p>At 80g per day — spread across 3–4 meals — most men over 40 are not clearing this threshold consistently. The result is a gradual, silent acceleration of <strong>sarcopenia</strong>: the age-related loss of muscle mass and strength that affects every man after 30, and accelerates sharply after 50 if protein intake stays low.</p>

    <div class="danger-box">
      <p><strong>The sarcopenia math:</strong> Men lose an average of 3–8% of muscle mass per decade after 30 under normal conditions. Research shows that men with chronically low protein intake — below the 1.2g/kg (0.55g/lb) threshold — experience significantly faster rates of muscle loss. That's not a small difference. Over a decade, the gap between 80g and 120g of daily protein could mean the difference between staying strong and struggling with basic physical tasks in your 60s and 70s.</p>
    </div>

    <p>The frustrating part: none of this is visible day to day. You don't feel muscle leaving. The scale might not even move. The process is slow and cumulative — which is exactly why most men don't connect their protein intake to how they feel and perform 10 years later.</p>

